{"title_page": "Book of Saint Cyprian", "text_new": "[[File:Kiprian and justina.JPG|thumb|Cyprian of Antioch (and Justina)]]\nThe '''Book of Saint Cyprian''' ({{lang-pt|Livro de S\u00e3o Cipriano}}; {{lang-es|Libro de San Cipriano}}) refers to different [[grimoire]]s from the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, all [[Pseudepigrapha|pseudepigraphically]] attributed to the 3rd century [[Cyprian and Justina|Saint Cyprian of Antioch]] (not to be confused with [[Cyprian|Saint Cyprian the bishop of Carthage]]). According to popular legend, Cyprian of Antioch was a pagan sorcerer who converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}{{sfn|Skinner|page=13-15}}{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n== The Iberian Cyprian ==\nThe Iberian Cyprian is not a single text but multiple texts in Spanish and Portuguese, mostly from the 19th century.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxiv-xxxv}}{{sfn|Castro}}{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  There was, however, a now lost pre-modern Cyprianic literature with no apparent connection to any extant works beyond being inspired by the Cyprianic legend.{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n=== The Portuguese Cyprian ===\nThe Portuguese version of the Book of Cyprian often bears prefixes such as \"Great and True,\" \"Only Complete,\" or \"Authentic,\"{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}} and typically subtitled \"The Sorcerer's Treasure\" (''ou thesouro de feiticeiro'').{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}}  The content is apparently Catholic, though deeply rooted in [[Brujer\u00eda|Bruxaria]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xvii}} and it is popular (particularly in [[Brazil]]) among practitioners of [[Quimbanda]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxv}} [[Umbanda]], and [[Candombl\u00e9]].{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  The Sorcerer's Treasure contains very little evocation,{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}} instead drawing upon oral traditions relating to [[divination]], [[Faith healing|healing spells]], [[prayer]]s{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}} (including some to one's [[guardian angel]]), [[exorcism]]s, [[love magic]], the locations of [[buried treasure]]s throughout [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], and sometimes even treatises on [[animal magnetism]] -- all set within a framework of [[folk Catholicism]].{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  Most editions start off with the legend of St Cyprian and commonly contain sections on [[alchemy]], [[astrology]], [[cartomancy]], [[Evocation|conjuring devils]], divination, [[exorcism]]s, [[ghost]]s, hidden treasures, love magic, luck magic, [[omen]]s, [[oneiromancy]], [[palmistry]], and prayers.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=v-ix}}  Some editions also contain the success stories of a French peasant named Victor Siderol, who purportedly discovered hidden treasures thanks to the book.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=v-ix}}{{sfn|Castro}}  The Brazilian forms of the Sorcerer's Treasure vary drastically, though the Portuguese editions are rather stable (at least in comparison).{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}}\n\nThe most representative edition is the ''Livraria Econ\u00f3mica'' edition,{{sfn|Castro}} which was translated into English as ''The Book of St. Cyprian - The Sorcerer's Treasure'' by Jos\u00e9 Leit\u00e3o with further additions from more recent editions (such as the ''Moderna Editorial Lavores'').{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxiii}}\n\nAccording to Leit\u00e3o, Portuguese Cyprianic literature represents a combination of Iberian magical beliefs and [[traditional African religion]].  The Portuguese Inquisition's focus on [[Crypto-Judaism]] (instead of witchcraft) made it easier for magical practitioners to Christianize traditional Iberian magical and imported African religious beliefs.  The Inquisition unintentionally aided this by treating [https://www.powerfulvoodoomagicspells.com/ traditional African religious practices] and beliefs as deviant forms of Catholicism rather than as something outside the religion.  Many of these practices were to have later influenced Portuguese Cyprianic literature.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|pages=xviii-xxiii}}  Leit\u00e3o further claims that Portuguese Cyprianic literature developed in three phases:{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}\n*the development of diverse oral traditions concerning St Cyprian.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxi}}\n*the collection of the oral traditions into a \"standard\" Book of Cyprian, which in turn gave rise to further oral traditions about the book itself.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxii}}\n*the standardized book being rearranged, expanded, and redacted with the advent of the printing press and South American syncretism.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxii-xxxiii}}\n\n=== The Spanish Cyprian ===\n[[File:El Libro Magno de San Cipriano. Tesoro del hechicero. Leipzig.jpg|thumb|The title page of a Spanish edition]]\nMost Spanish version claim to have been written by a Jonas Sulfurino (\"Sulphury Jonas\"), are similar (though distinct from) the [[Key of Solomon]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxvi-xxviii}} and are typically a rehash of the Grand Grimoire.{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  The most complete and popular version, titled ''Libro Infernal'', combines elements of the Grand Grimoire, the Key of Solomon, and the ''Grand et [[Petit Albert]]''.  The ''Libro Infernal'' was also translated to Italian in 1920 by its original publisher.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxvi-xxviii}}\n\nThe oldest extant Cyprianic work dates to 1810 and claims to have been translated from Latin.  It is titled \"Heptameron or [https://www.powerfulvoodoomagicspells.com/ Magical Elements],\" but despite this title bears little resemblance to [[Pietro_d'Abano#Writings|the purported grimoire by Pietro d'Abano]] or any other European [https://www.powerfulvoodoomagicspells.com/ spell book].  Later, an edition of the [[Grand Grimoire]] was appended to a book on the Galician Inquisition, claimed to be \"the Ciprianillo.\"  Following this was another edition of the Grand Grimoire which added the supposed copyist-monk Jon\u00e1s Sufurino to the legend.  Later editions added material on animal magnetism, cartomancy, [[hypnotism]], [[Spiritualism]], and ''The [[Black Pullet]]''.{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n== The Scandinavian Cyprian ==\n{{main article|Cyprianus}}\nThe Scandinavian [[Cyprianus]] ''svarteboken'' (black books) are a distinct tradition with no connection beyond the shared story of St Cyprian.{{sfn|Skinner|page=16-19}}  One of these, the ''Black Books of Elvarum'', dates back to 1682 and claims to go back to 1529.<ref>Mary Rustad, ''The Black Books of Elverum'' (Galde Press, 1999; {{ISBN|1-880090-75-9}}), p.xxxvii, 1, 5</ref>\n\n== The Wellcome Cyprian ==\nA Latin manuscript (Wellcome MS 2000) attributed to \"M: L: Cypriani\" (or \"Magistri Ludi Cypriani,\" 'teacher Cypriani') entitled ''Clavis Inferni sive magia alba et nigra approbata Metratona'' ('The Key of Hell with white and [https://www.powerfulvoodoomagicspells.com/black-magic-spells/ black magic] proven by Metatron'){{sfn|Skinner|page=12}} was discovered by Stephen Skinner and David Rankine in 2004.{{sfn|Skinner|page=28}}  It dates to either 1717 or 1757,{{sfn|Skinner|page=25}} though internal evidence suggests 1857 as another possible date.{{sfn|Skinner|page=27}}\n\nIt is unrelated to Iberian or Scandinavian Cyprianic literature (beyond its patron saint),{{sfn|Skinner|pages=16,19}} but is definitely related to pseudo-d'Abano's Heptameron,{{sfn|Skinner|page=19}} [[Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa]], the [[Sixth and Seventh Books of Moses]], contemporary ''[[Faustbuch]]en'' from ''[[Das Kloster]]'',{{sfn|Skinner|page=23-25}} ''Liber Lunae'',{{sfn|Skinner|page=37}} [[Trithemius]]'s ''Polygraphie'', and the [[Magical Calendar]]{{sfn|Skinner|pages=26-27,84}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://danharms.wordpress.com/the-books-of-saint-cyprian/\n| last = Castro\n| first = F\u00e9lix Francisco \n| editor-last = Harms\n| editor-first = Dan\n| editor-link = Daniel Harms\n| title = The Books of Saint Cyprian\n| website = Papers Falling from an Attic Window\n| date = 2010\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Leit\u00e3o\n| first = Jos\u00e9\n| title = The Book of St. Cyprian - The Sorcerer's Treasure\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=X9LZoAEACAAJ\n| publisher = Hadean press\n| date = 2014\n| ref = harv\n| isbn = 9781907881329\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Skinner\n| first1 = Stephen\n| last2 = Rankine\n| first2 = David\n| title = The Grimoire of Saint Cyprian - Clavis Inferni\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7cSRRAAACAAJ\n| publisher = Llewellyn Worldwide Limited\n| date = 2010\n| ref = harv\n| isbn = 9780738723488\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.religiosidadepopular.uaivip.com.br/cipriano.htm Religiosidade Popular]\n* [http://www.iapsop.com/ssoc/1905__sufurino___libro_de_san_cipriano_verdadera_magia.pdf A 1905 Spanish edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great Book of Saint Cyprian}}\n[[Category:Grimoires]]\n[[Category:Occult books]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kiprian and justina.JPG|thumb|Cyprian of Antioch (and Justina)]]\nThe '''Book of Saint Cyprian''' ({{lang-pt|Livro de S\u00e3o Cipriano}}; {{lang-es|Libro de San Cipriano}}) refers to different [[grimoire]]s from the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, all [[Pseudepigrapha|pseudepigraphically]] attributed to the 3rd century [[Cyprian and Justina|Saint Cyprian of Antioch]] (not to be confused with [[Cyprian|Saint Cyprian the bishop of Carthage]]). According to popular legend, Cyprian of Antioch was a pagan sorcerer who converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}{{sfn|Skinner|page=13-15}}{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n== The Iberian Cyprian ==\nThe Iberian Cyprian is not a single text but multiple texts in Spanish and Portuguese, mostly from the 19th century.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxiv-xxxv}}{{sfn|Castro}}{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  There was, however, a now lost pre-modern Cyprianic literature with no apparent connection to any extant works beyond being inspired by the Cyprianic legend.{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n=== The Portuguese Cyprian ===\nThe Portuguese version of the Book of Cyprian often bears prefixes such as \"Great and True,\" \"Only Complete,\" or \"Authentic,\"{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}} and typically subtitled \"The Sorcerer's Treasure\" (''ou thesouro de feiticeiro'').{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}}  The content is apparently Catholic, though deeply rooted in [[Brujer\u00eda|Bruxaria]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xvii}} and it is popular (particularly in [[Brazil]]) among practitioners of [[Quimbanda]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxv}} [[Umbanda]], and [[Candombl\u00e9]].{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  The Sorcerer's Treasure contains very little evocation,{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}} instead drawing upon oral traditions relating to [[divination]], [[Faith healing|healing spells]], [[prayer]]s{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}} (including some to one's [[guardian angel]]), [[exorcism]]s, [[love magic]], the locations of [[buried treasure]]s throughout [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], and sometimes even treatises on [[animal magnetism]] -- all set within a framework of [[folk Catholicism]].{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  Most editions start off with the legend of St Cyprian and commonly contain sections on [[alchemy]], [[astrology]], [[cartomancy]], [[Evocation|conjuring devils]], divination, [[exorcism]]s, [[ghost]]s, hidden treasures, love magic, luck magic, [[omen]]s, [[oneiromancy]], [[palmistry]], and prayers.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=v-ix}}  Some editions also contain the success stories of a French peasant named Victor Siderol, who purportedly discovered hidden treasures thanks to the book.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=v-ix}}{{sfn|Castro}}  The Brazilian forms of the Sorcerer's Treasure vary drastically, though the Portuguese editions are rather stable (at least in comparison).{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxviii}}\n\nThe most representative edition is the ''Livraria Econ\u00f3mica'' edition,{{sfn|Castro}} which was translated into English as ''The Book of St. Cyprian - The Sorcerer's Treasure'' by Jos\u00e9 Leit\u00e3o with further additions from more recent editions (such as the ''Moderna Editorial Lavores'').{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxiii}}\n\nAccording to Leit\u00e3o, Portuguese Cyprianic literature represents a combination of Iberian magical beliefs and [[traditional African religion]].  The Portuguese Inquisition's focus on [[Crypto-Judaism]] (instead of witchcraft) made it easier for magical practitioners to Christianize traditional Iberian magical and imported African religious beliefs.  The Inquisition unintentionally aided this by treating traditional African religious practices and beliefs as deviant forms of Catholicism rather than as something outside the religion.  Many of these practices were to have later influenced Portuguese Cyprianic literature.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|pages=xviii-xxiii}}  Leit\u00e3o further claims that Portuguese Cyprianic literature developed in three phases:{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxiii}}\n*the development of diverse oral traditions concerning St Cyprian.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxix-xxxi}}\n*the collection of the oral traditions into a \"standard\" Book of Cyprian, which in turn gave rise to further oral traditions about the book itself.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxii}}\n*the standardized book being rearranged, expanded, and redacted with the advent of the printing press and South American syncretism.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxxii-xxxiii}}\n\n=== The Spanish Cyprian ===\n[[File:El Libro Magno de San Cipriano. Tesoro del hechicero. Leipzig.jpg|thumb|The title page of a Spanish edition]]\nMost Spanish version claim to have been written by a Jonas Sulfurino (\"Sulphury Jonas\"), are similar (though distinct from) the [[Key of Solomon]],{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxvi-xxviii}} and are typically a rehash of the Grand Grimoire.{{sfn|Skinner|page=15-16}}  The most complete and popular version, titled ''Libro Infernal'', combines elements of the Grand Grimoire, the Key of Solomon, and the ''Grand et [[Petit Albert]]''.  The ''Libro Infernal'' was also translated to Italian in 1920 by its original publisher.{{sfn|Leit\u00e3o|page=xxvi-xxviii}}\n\nThe oldest extant Cyprianic work dates to 1810 and claims to have been translated from Latin.  It is titled \"Heptameron or Magical Elements,\" but despite this title bears little resemblance to [[Pietro_d'Abano#Writings|the purported grimoire by Pietro d'Abano]] or any other European spell book.  Later, an edition of the [[Grand Grimoire]] was appended to a book on the Galician Inquisition, claimed to be \"the Ciprianillo.\"  Following this was another edition of the Grand Grimoire which added the supposed copyist-monk Jon\u00e1s Sufurino to the legend.  Later editions added material on animal magnetism, cartomancy, [[hypnotism]], [[Spiritualism]], and ''The [[Black Pullet]]''.{{sfn|Castro}}\n\n== The Scandinavian Cyprian ==\n{{main article|Cyprianus}}\nThe Scandinavian [[Cyprianus]] ''svarteboken'' (black books) are a distinct tradition with no connection beyond the shared story of St Cyprian.{{sfn|Skinner|page=16-19}}  One of these, the ''Black Books of Elvarum'', dates back to 1682 and claims to go back to 1529.<ref>Mary Rustad, ''The Black Books of Elverum'' (Galde Press, 1999; {{ISBN|1-880090-75-9}}), p.xxxvii, 1, 5</ref>\n\n== The Wellcome Cyprian ==\nA Latin manuscript (Wellcome MS 2000) attributed to \"M: L: Cypriani\" (or \"Magistri Ludi Cypriani,\" 'teacher Cypriani') entitled ''Clavis Inferni sive magia alba et nigra approbata Metratona'' ('The Key of Hell with white and black magic proven by Metatron'){{sfn|Skinner|page=12}} was discovered by Stephen Skinner and David Rankine in 2004.{{sfn|Skinner|page=28}}  It dates to either 1717 or 1757,{{sfn|Skinner|page=25}} though internal evidence suggests 1857 as another possible date.{{sfn|Skinner|page=27}}\n\nIt is unrelated to Iberian or Scandinavian Cyprianic literature (beyond its patron saint),{{sfn|Skinner|pages=16,19}} but is definitely related to pseudo-d'Abano's Heptameron,{{sfn|Skinner|page=19}} [[Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa]], the [[Sixth and Seventh Books of Moses]], contemporary ''[[Faustbuch]]en'' from ''[[Das Kloster]]'',{{sfn|Skinner|page=23-25}} ''Liber Lunae'',{{sfn|Skinner|page=37}} [[Trithemius]]'s ''Polygraphie'', and the [[Magical Calendar]]{{sfn|Skinner|pages=26-27,84}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://danharms.wordpress.com/the-books-of-saint-cyprian/\n| last = Castro\n| first = F\u00e9lix Francisco \n| editor-last = Harms\n| editor-first = Dan\n| editor-link = Daniel Harms\n| title = The Books of Saint Cyprian\n| website = Papers Falling from an Attic Window\n| date = 2010\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Leit\u00e3o\n| first = Jos\u00e9\n| title = The Book of St. Cyprian - The Sorcerer's Treasure\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=X9LZoAEACAAJ\n| publisher = Hadean press\n| date = 2014\n| ref = harv\n| isbn = 9781907881329\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Skinner\n| first1 = Stephen\n| last2 = Rankine\n| first2 = David\n| title = The Grimoire of Saint Cyprian - Clavis Inferni\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7cSRRAAACAAJ\n| publisher = Llewellyn Worldwide Limited\n| date = 2010\n| ref = harv\n| isbn = 9780738723488\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.religiosidadepopular.uaivip.com.br/cipriano.htm Religiosidade Popular]\n* [http://www.iapsop.com/ssoc/1905__sufurino___libro_de_san_cipriano_verdadera_magia.pdf A 1905 Spanish edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great Book of Saint Cyprian}}\n[[Category:Grimoires]]\n[[Category:Occult books]]\n", "name_user": "Folkshore323", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThe Spanish Cyprian)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Saint_Cyprian"}
{"title_page": "Assam Public Service Commission", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{unreferenced|date=February 2018}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name              = Assam Public Service Commission\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_a     = \n| native_name_r     = \n| type              = Commission\n| seal              = \n| seal_width        = \n| seal_caption      = \n| logo              =  [[File:Seal of Assam.svg|200px]]\n| logo_width        = \n| logo_caption      = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| image_caption     =\n| formed            = {{Start date|df=yes|1937|04|01}}\n| preceding1        = State Public Service Commission\n| preceding2        = Public Service Commission\n| dissolved         = \n| superseding1      = \n| superseding2      = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction      = [[State of Assam]]\n| headquarters      = APSC Building , Jawahar nagar, Khanapara, Assam\n| coordinates       = \n| motto             = \n| employees         = \n| budget            = \n| minister1_name    = \n| minister1_pfo     = \n| minister2_name    = \n| minister2_pfo     = <!-- up to |minister8_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo  = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo  = <!-- up to |deputyminister8_name= -->\n| chief1_name       = Pallab Bhattacharyya, Ex IPS <!-- up to |chief9_name= -->\n| chief1_position   = Chairman\n| chief2_name       = Sanjib Gohain Baruah, IAS\n| chief2_position   = Member\n| chief3_name       = Niranjan Kalita\n| chief3_position   = Member\n| chief4_name       = \n| chief4_position   = \n| chief5_name       = \n| chief5_position   = \n| chief6_name       = \n| chief6_position   = \n| chief7_name       = \n| chief7_position   = \n| chief8_name       = \n| chief8_position   = \n| chief9_name       = \n| chief9_position   = \n| public_protector  =\n| deputy            =\n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency     = \n| child1_agency     = \n| keydocument1      = <!-- up to |keydocument6= -->\n| website           = {{URL|apsc.nic.in}}\n| map               = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| footnotes         = \n| embed             =\n}}\nThe '''Assam Public Service commission''' ('''APSC''') is an Indian government agency headquartered at Jawahar Nagar, [[Khanapara]] in [[Guwahati]] and functions through its own secretariat.  Shri Pallab Bhattacharyya, IPS (Retd.) is its current Chairman.{{update inline|date=September 2019}}\n\nEstablished on 1 April 1937 as Public Service Commission,  in accordance with the provision of the Govt. of India Act, 1935.\nAPSC EXAMPLE SYLLABUS 2020.([https://www.physicsnews.today/2020/04/apsc-cce-syllabus-exam-pattern-2020-new.html?m=1 SYLLABUS)] \n\n== Functions ==\n\nAs mentioned in [[Part XIV of the Constitution of India|Article 320]], Part XIV of the [[Constitution of India]], the Commission shall be consulted on all matters relating to recruitment to civil services and posts in state of [[Assam]]  .The Assam Public Service Commission has to discharge the duties and functions as specified in its Regulations, the prime duties and functions of the Commission are: <br />\n\n1. To recommend candidates for Direct Recruitment to the various services of the State Government. <br />\n2. To advise the Government on the principles to be followed to assess the suitability of the officers for promotion. <br />\n3. To advise the Govt. on all disciplinary matters affecting the person serving under the Government within the purview of the Commission;<br />\n4.  To advise the Government on all matters relating to framing of Recruitment Rules/Draft Service Rules of different departments of the Government; <br />\n5.  To advise the Government relating to the method of recruitment to Civil Services; <br />\n6.  To advise the Government on matters relating to protection and fixation of pay, in respect of Government servants, who were initially appointed as per recommendation of the Commission; <br />\n7.  To conduct Departmental examinations for Government services. <br />\n\n== Reference ==\n\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Assam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{unreferenced|date=February 2018}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name              = Assam Public Service Commission\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_a     = \n| native_name_r     = \n| type              = Commission\n| seal              = \n| seal_width        = \n| seal_caption      = \n| logo              =  [[File:Seal of Assam.svg|200px]]\n| logo_width        = \n| logo_caption      = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| image_caption     =\n| formed            = {{Start date|df=yes|1937|04|01}}\n| preceding1        = State Public Service Commission\n| preceding2        = Public Service Commission\n| dissolved         = \n| superseding1      = \n| superseding2      = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction      = [[State of Assam]]\n| headquarters      = APSC Building , Jawahar nagar, Khanapara, Assam\n| coordinates       = \n| motto             = \n| employees         = \n| budget            = \n| minister1_name    = \n| minister1_pfo     = \n| minister2_name    = \n| minister2_pfo     = <!-- up to |minister8_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo  = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo  = <!-- up to |deputyminister8_name= -->\n| chief1_name       = Pallab Bhattacharyya, Ex IPS <!-- up to |chief9_name= -->\n| chief1_position   = Chairman\n| chief2_name       = Sanjib Gohain Baruah, IAS\n| chief2_position   = Member\n| chief3_name       = Niranjan Kalita\n| chief3_position   = Member\n| chief4_name       = \n| chief4_position   = \n| chief5_name       = \n| chief5_position   = \n| chief6_name       = \n| chief6_position   = \n| chief7_name       = \n| chief7_position   = \n| chief8_name       = \n| chief8_position   = \n| chief9_name       = \n| chief9_position   = \n| public_protector  =\n| deputy            =\n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency     = \n| child1_agency     = \n| keydocument1      = <!-- up to |keydocument6= -->\n| website           = {{URL|apsc.nic.in}}\n| map               = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| footnotes         = \n| embed             =\n}}\nThe '''Assam Public Service commission''' ('''APSC''') is an Indian government agency headquartered at Jawahar Nagar, [[Khanapara]] in [[Guwahati]] and functions through its own secretariat.  Shri Pallab Bhattacharyya, IPS (Retd.) is its current Chairman.{{update inline|date=September 2019}}\n\nEstablished on 1 April 1937 as Public Service Commission,  in accordance with the provision of the Govt. of India Act, 1935.\n\n== Functions ==\n\nAs mentioned in [[Part XIV of the Constitution of India|Article 320]], Part XIV of the [[Constitution of India]], the Commission shall be consulted on all matters relating to recruitment to civil services and posts in state of [[Assam]]  .The Assam Public Service Commission has to discharge the duties and functions as specified in its Regulations, the prime duties and functions of the Commission are: <br />\n\n1. To recommend candidates for Direct Recruitment to the various services of the State Government. <br />\n2. To advise the Government on the principles to be followed to assess the suitability of the officers for promotion. <br />\n3. To advise the Govt. on all disciplinary matters affecting the person serving under the Government within the purview of the Commission;<br />\n4.  To advise the Government on all matters relating to framing of Recruitment Rules/Draft Service Rules of different departments of the Government; <br />\n5.  To advise the Government relating to the method of recruitment to Civil Services; <br />\n6.  To advise the Government on matters relating to protection and fixation of pay, in respect of Government servants, who were initially appointed as per recommendation of the Commission; <br />\n7.  To conduct Departmental examinations for Government services. <br />\n\n== Reference ==\n\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Assam]]\n", "name_user": "Abhibro1", "label": "safe", "comment": "I just add only syllabus of APSC exam 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assam_Public_Service_Commission"}
{"title_page": "Francis Durning", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n\n\n'''Francis (Frank) Durning''' [[Society of Mary (Marists)|SM]] was a New Zealand [[priest]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. \n\nDurning was born in [[Glasgow]] on 12 May 1914, and his family emmigrated to New Zealand. He was ordained as a priest with the Society of Mary (Marist) on 11 December 1938.\n\nDurning taught in Catholic institutions from the 1940s through to the late 1980s, among others at:\n* Saint Bede's College, Wellington \n* Chanel College in Samoa\n* Saint Patrick's College in Silverstream, where he was Rector of the school from 1950-1955\n* Saint Patrick's College in Wellington\n\nDurning passed away on 13 April 1999.\n\nIn 2018 the Society of Mary admitted that Francis Durning sexually abused children.<ref name=\"no records\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/375653/wellington-catholic-school-has-no-records-of-sex-abuse|title=Wellington Catholic school has no records of sex abuse|date=11 November 2018|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128082612/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/375653/wellington-catholic-school-has-no-records-of-sex-abuse|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>Radio New Zealand cites a victim, whose complaint was upheld by the Society of Mary in 2009, alleging that the During was known as \"Fred the Fiddler\" by his own colleagues.<ref name=\"no records\"></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Durning, Francis}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Dead people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Paedophiles]]\n[[Category:Oaedophile priests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n\n\n'''Francis (Frank) Durning''' [[Society of Mary (Marists)|SM]] was a New Zealand [[priest]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. \n\nDurning was born in [[Glasgow]] on 12 May 1914, and his family emmigrated to New Zealand. He was ordained as a priest with the Society of Mary (Marist) on 11 December 1938.\n\nDurning taught in Catholic institutions from the 1940s through to the late 1980s, among others at:\n* Saint Bede's College, Wellington \n* Chanel College in Samoa\n* Saint Patrick's College in Silverstream, where he was head master of the school\n* Saint Patrick's College in Wellington\n\nDurning passed away on 13 April 1999.\n\nIn 2018 the Society of Mary admitted that Francis Durning sexually abused children.<ref name=\"no records\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/375653/wellington-catholic-school-has-no-records-of-sex-abuse|title=Wellington Catholic school has no records of sex abuse|date=11 November 2018|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128082612/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/375653/wellington-catholic-school-has-no-records-of-sex-abuse|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Durning, Francis}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Dead people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Paedophiles]]\n[[Category:Oaedophile priests]]\n", "name_user": "Marchonore", "label": "safe", "comment": "added status as school rector", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Durning"}
{"title_page": "Willaston, Cheshire East", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|53.082|-2.479|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Willaston\n| label_position           = top\n| population               = 3,104\n| population_ref           = (2011)\n| static_image             = Willaston Mike Heywood Green.jpg\n| static_image_caption     = Mike Heywood Green Willaston\n| shire_district           = \n| unitary_england          = [[Cheshire East]]\n| shire_county             = [[Cheshire]]\n| region                   = North West England\n| civil_parish             = Willaston\n| constituency_westminster = [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]]\n| postcode_district        = CW5\n| postcode_area            = CW\n| post_town                = Crewe\n| dial_code                = 01270 (Crewe)\n| os_grid_reference        = SJ682539\n| london_distance          = \n}}\n'''Willaston''' is a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and village in the unitary authority of [[Cheshire East]] and the ceremonial county of [[Cheshire]], in north-west [[England]]. It has a population of 2,277<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/ |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref> people according to the 2001 [[census]], increasing to 3,104 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11130674&c=Willaston&d=16&e=62&g=6407854&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458056475214&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=15 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nIt is approximately three miles west of [[Crewe]] town centre and two miles east of [[Nantwich]] town centre. Willaston has very good transport links being approximately 7 miles from junction 16 of the M6 and 3 miles from [[Crewe railway station]].\n\n==Governance==\nFrom 1974 to 2009 the Borough Council was [[Crewe and Nantwich]]. Since this was abolished on 1 April 2009, the civil parish has been administered by the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Cheshire East]].<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080634_en_2#pt2-l1g3 Cheshire (Structural Changes) Order 2008]</ref>\n\nWillaston Parish Council was established in 1894 and is the first tier of local government for Willaston. Willaston Parish Council is responsible for the management of the Lettie Spencer Playing Field, The War Memorial on Colleys Lane, the village allotments on Crewe Road, The Spinney off Coppice Road and Mike Heywood Green. The Council is made up of 12 members from two wards who represent the interests of all Willaston Residents.<ref>[https://www.willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/ Willaston Parish Council], Willason Parish Council Website. Retrieved: 30 October 2019.</ref>\n\nWillaston falls in the parliamentary constituency of [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]],<ref>[http://maps.cheshire.gov.uk/cheshirecc.interactivemapping.web.internet/Default.aspx?e=370949&n=351148&mpp=25&layers=BOU.PLA.PLO.PAR.WCON&hLayer=WCON&hField=OBJECTID&hValue=19 Cheshire County Council: Interactive Mapping: Crewe and Nantwich]. Retrieved 27 January 2009.</ref> which has been represented by [[Kieran Mullan]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]].\n\n== History of Willaston ==\nWillaston is believed to have taken its name from an ancient farmstead known as Wiglaf's tun. Like other English villages, the name has been changed many times over the centuries. This is due to the neighbouring parish of Wistaston having a similar sounding name. To add confusion, Willaston was once ecclesiastically divided between the neighbouring communities of Nantwich and Wybunbury.\n\nWhilst there are at least two other villages called Willaston, the earliest documentary evidence relating to Willaston in this part of Cheshire can be found in the [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] survey of 1086, where is it referred to as Wilavestune. We know by reading this document that a 'free man' by the name of Ulviet once owned Wilvastune and that, just a few years after the Norman conquest, the title passed to Willam Malbank. The manor of Wilvastune remained in the Malbank family for several generations before ownership transferred to the Chanu family in the 13th century.\n\nAt this time, Willaston was a remote, sparsely populated community with no village centre. Nevertheless, it covered a much larger area than it does today, stretching from Newcastle Road and London Road Nantwich in the south, along Millstone Lane and as far as the ancient grazing land of Beam Heath in the north. These boundaries did not change until 1936, when local government decided to transfer some of Willaston's land to the expanding communities of [[Nantwich]] and Stapeley. In 1553, the manor of Willaston was bought by Richard Sneyd. Recorder of Chester. The Sneyd family lived at [[Keele Hall]] in Staffordshire and were the major landowners in WIllaston until the middle of the 19th century.\n\nAlthough Willaston had a number of farmsteads in the Middle Ages, most of the surrounding landscape was uncultivated. However, this began to change as more and more common land began to fall into private ownership during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The process (known as 'enclosure') brought major changes to rural communities such as Willaston, as individual plots of land were fenced off and used for arable farming, meadows and the grazing of livestock. The Sneyd family were absentee landlords but they owned most of the lands in Willaston from 1533 to the late 19th century.\n\nUnfortunately, the medieval moated site of the Chanu family was lost during the construction of the Nantwich by-pass in 1989. It was situated to the south-east of the Old Willaston Board School on land now owned by Cheerbrook Farm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/files/Willaston_Parish_Plan_2009.pdf|title=Willaston Parish Plan - History of Willaston|last=|first=|date=|website=Willaston Parish Council|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities==\nThe village centre of Willaston has two [[public house]]s (The Lamb and The Nag's Head) and a social club, while an [[off-licence]] provides local produce and day to day goods. Another pub, The Peacock, is situated to the north-west of the village centre, on Crewe Road (the [[A534 road|A534]]). Alongside The Peacock pub is a hotel operated by [[Premier Inn]].\n \nThe social club offers many social events ranging from a monthly kids disco to various tribute bands and acts.  The club has two pool teams, a [[snooker]] team, two 7-a-side [[Association football|football]] teams, a darts and [[dominoes]] team and a ladies [[darts]] team. In summer 2013 the function room (available for hire) was refurbished.\n\nThe village also has a fish and chip shop, and hairdressing salons. There are local businesses within the village providing employment (Scanlans, SJB Steel). At the edge of the village is a farm shop, Cheerbrook,<ref>[http://www.cheerbrook.co.uk Cheerbrook Farm's Official Website] . Retrieved 31 January 2009.</ref> on the Newcastle Road. A plant nursery and garden centre is located on Crewe Road.\n\nWillaston Primary School<ref>[http://clc2.uniservity.com/Grouphomepage.asp?GroupId=71339 Willaston Primary School Website] . Retrieved May 18th 2010.</ref> is the only education establishment in the village. For children of pre-school age, there is an Ofsted registered playgroup in the village.\n\nA [[Red telephone box|K6]] telephone box is located in the village on Wistaston Road and has been in place since the late 1940s. The box was decommissioned by [[BT Group|British Telecom]] in 2010. The telephone box was purchased by Willaston Parish Council and turned into a book exchange known as the book box. A restoration was carried out in September 2019.\n[[File:Willaston_Book_Box.jpg|thumb|Former K6 Telephone box converted into a book exchange box]]\n\n==Local events==\n[[File:Willaston - Worm Charming.jpg|thumb|right|The [[World Worm Charming Championships]] have been held in Willaston since 1980.]]\nOne of the major events in Willaston is the [[World Worm Charming Championships]]. It was started in 1980 by John Bailey. The event attracts many competitors from around the world, from the U.S. to Australia. The original event in 1980 was won with a total of 511 worms by Tom Shufflebotham - a record that stood until 2009.\n\nCelebrities that have taken part in the championships include [[Ben Fogle]] and [[Bob Carolgees]]. In 2008 celebrity contestants [[Paddy McGuinness]] and [[Rory McGrath]] filmed a slot for their series \"Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demand.five.tv/Episode.aspx?episodeBaseName=C5141230003 |title=Demand Five &#124; watch Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure, Series 1 - episode 3, Episode 3 |publisher=Demand.five.tv |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 championship was won by Mike and Claire Gaukroger with a total of 125 worms; the trophy for the heaviest worm went to Ray O'Grady and Steve Plant (4.6g).<ref>{{cite web |author=Nicola King on behalf of I.F.C.W.A.P. |url=http://www.wormcharming.com |title=The World Worm Charming Championships |publisher=Wormcharming.com |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504122657/http://www.wormcharming.com/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, due to particularly good conditions, three teams broke the previous world record of 511. Sophie Smith and Matt Smith of Willaston claimed the title with a total of 567 worms in 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5664058/The-charms-of-worm-charming.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=The charms of worm charming | first=William | last=Langley | date=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Willaston Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Willaston, Cheshire East}}\n\n{{Cheshire, Cheshire East}}\n{{Cheshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cheshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|53.082|-2.479|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Willaston\n| label_position           = top\n| population               = 3,104\n| population_ref           = (2011)\n| static_image             = Willaston Mike Heywood Green.jpg\n| static_image_caption     = Mike Heywood Green Willaston\n| shire_district           = \n| unitary_england          = [[Cheshire East]]\n| shire_county             = [[Cheshire]]\n| region                   = North West England\n| civil_parish             = Willaston\n| constituency_westminster = [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]]\n| postcode_district        = CW5\n| postcode_area            = CW\n| post_town                = Crewe\n| dial_code                = 01270 (Crewe)\n| os_grid_reference        = SJ682539\n| london_distance          = \n}}\n'''Willaston''' is a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and village in the unitary authority of [[Cheshire East]] and the ceremonial county of [[Cheshire]], in north-west [[England]]. It has a population of 2,277<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/ |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref> people according to the 2001 [[census]], increasing to 3,104 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11130674&c=Willaston&d=16&e=62&g=6407854&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458056475214&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=15 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nIt is approximately three miles west of [[Crewe]] town centre and two miles east of [[Nantwich]] town centre. Willaston has very good transport links being approximately 7 miles from junction 16 of the M6 and 3 miles from [[Crewe railway station]].\n\n==Governance==\nFrom 1974 to 2009 the Borough Council was [[Crewe and Nantwich]]. Since this was abolished on 1 April 2009, the civil parish has been administered by the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Cheshire East]].<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080634_en_2#pt2-l1g3 Cheshire (Structural Changes) Order 2008]</ref>\n\nWillaston Parish Council was established in 1894 and is responsible for the management of the Lettie Spencer Playing Field, The War Memorial on Colleys Lane, the village allotments on Crewe Road, The Spinney off Coppice Road and Mike Heywood Green. The Council is made up of 12 members from two wards who represent the interests of all Willaston Residents.<ref>[https://www.willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/ Willaston Parish Council], Willason Parish Council Website. Retrieved: 30 October 2019.</ref>\n\nWillaston falls in the parliamentary constituency of [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]],<ref>[http://maps.cheshire.gov.uk/cheshirecc.interactivemapping.web.internet/Default.aspx?e=370949&n=351148&mpp=25&layers=BOU.PLA.PLO.PAR.WCON&hLayer=WCON&hField=OBJECTID&hValue=19 Cheshire County Council: Interactive Mapping: Crewe and Nantwich]. Retrieved 27 January 2009.</ref> which has been represented by [[Kieran Mullan]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]].\n\n== History of Willaston ==\nWillaston is believed to have taken its name from an ancient farmstead known as Wiglaf's tun. Like other English villages, the name has been changed many times over the centuries. This is due to the neighbouring parish of Wistaston having a similar sounding name. To add confusion, Willaston was once ecclesiastically divided between the neighbouring communities of Nantwich and Wybunbury.\n\nWhilst there are at least two other villages called Willaston, the earliest documentary evidence relating to Willaston in this part of Cheshire can be found in the [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] survey of 1086, where is it referred to as Wilavestune. We know by reading this document that a 'free man' by the name of Ulviet once owned Wilvastune and that, just a few years after the Norman conquest, the title passed to Willam Malbank. The manor of Wilvastune remained in the Malbank family for several generations before ownership transferred to the Chanu family in the 13th century.\n\nAt this time, Willaston was a remote, sparsely populated community with no village centre. Nevertheless, it covered a much larger area than it does today, stretching from Newcastle Road and London Road Nantwich in the south, along Millstone Lane and as far as the ancient grazing land of Beam Heath in the north. These boundaries did not change until 1936, when local government decided to transfer some of Willaston's land to the expanding communities of [[Nantwich]] and Stapeley. In 1553, the manor of Willaston was bought by Richard Sneyd. Recorder of Chester. The Sneyd family lived at [[Keele Hall]] in Staffordshire and were the major landowners in WIllaston until the middle of the 19th century.\n\nAlthough Willaston had a number of farmsteads in the Middle Ages, most of the surrounding landscape was uncultivated. However, this began to change as more and more common land began to fall into private ownership during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The process (known as 'enclosure') brought major changes to rural communities such as Willaston, as individual plots of land were fenced off and used for arable farming, meadows and the grazing of livestock. The Sneyd family were absentee landlords but they owned most of the lands in Willaston from 1533 to the late 19th century.\n\nUnfortunately, the medieval moated site of the Chanu family was lost during the construction of the Nantwich by-pass in 1989. It was situated to the south-east of the Old Willaston Board School on land now owned by Cheerbrook Farm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/files/Willaston_Parish_Plan_2009.pdf|title=Willaston Parish Plan - History of Willaston|last=|first=|date=|website=Willaston Parish Council|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities==\nThe village centre of Willaston has two [[public house]]s (The Lamb and The Nag's Head) and a social club, while an [[off-licence]] provides local produce and day to day goods. Another pub, The Peacock, is situated to the north-west of the village centre, on Crewe Road (the [[A534 road|A534]]). Alongside The Peacock pub is a hotel operated by [[Premier Inn]].\n \nThe social club offers many social events ranging from a monthly kids disco to various tribute bands and acts.  The club has two pool teams, a [[snooker]] team, two 7-a-side [[Association football|football]] teams, a darts and [[dominoes]] team and a ladies [[darts]] team. In summer 2013 the function room (available for hire) was refurbished.\n\nThe village also has a fish and chip shop, and hairdressing salons. There are local businesses within the village providing employment (Scanlans, SJB Steel). At the edge of the village is a farm shop, Cheerbrook,<ref>[http://www.cheerbrook.co.uk Cheerbrook Farm's Official Website] . Retrieved 31 January 2009.</ref> on the Newcastle Road. A plant nursery and garden centre is located on Crewe Road.\n\nWillaston Primary School<ref>[http://clc2.uniservity.com/Grouphomepage.asp?GroupId=71339 Willaston Primary School Website] . Retrieved May 18th 2010.</ref> is the only education establishment in the village. For children of pre-school age, there is an Ofsted registered playgroup in the village.\n\nA [[Red telephone box|K6]] telephone box is located in the village on Wistaston Road and has been in place since the late 1940s. The box was decommissioned by [[BT Group|British Telecom]] in 2010. The telephone box was purchased by Willaston Parish Council and turned into a book exchange known as the book box. A restoration was carried out in September 2019.\n[[File:Willaston_Book_Box.jpg|thumb|Former K6 Telephone box converted into a book exchange box]]\n\n==Local events==\n[[File:Willaston - Worm Charming.jpg|thumb|right|The [[World Worm Charming Championships]] have been held in Willaston since 1980.]]\nOne of the major events in Willaston is the [[World Worm Charming Championships]]. It was started in 1980 by John Bailey. The event attracts many competitors from around the world, from the U.S. to Australia. The original event in 1980 was won with a total of 511 worms by Tom Shufflebotham - a record that stood until 2009.\n\nCelebrities that have taken part in the championships include [[Ben Fogle]] and [[Bob Carolgees]]. In 2008 celebrity contestants [[Paddy McGuinness]] and [[Rory McGrath]] filmed a slot for their series \"Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demand.five.tv/Episode.aspx?episodeBaseName=C5141230003 |title=Demand Five &#124; watch Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure, Series 1 - episode 3, Episode 3 |publisher=Demand.five.tv |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 championship was won by Mike and Claire Gaukroger with a total of 125 worms; the trophy for the heaviest worm went to Ray O'Grady and Steve Plant (4.6g).<ref>{{cite web |author=Nicola King on behalf of I.F.C.W.A.P. |url=http://www.wormcharming.com |title=The World Worm Charming Championships |publisher=Wormcharming.com |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504122657/http://www.wormcharming.com/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, due to particularly good conditions, three teams broke the previous world record of 511. Sophie Smith and Matt Smith of Willaston claimed the title with a total of 567 worms in 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5664058/The-charms-of-worm-charming.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=The charms of worm charming | first=William | last=Langley | date=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Willaston Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Willaston, Cheshire East}}\n\n{{Cheshire, Cheshire East}}\n{{Cheshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cheshire]]\n", "name_user": "Waynes78", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willaston,_Cheshire_East"}
{"title_page": "A. H. Almaas", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=March 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=March 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = A. H. Almaas\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1944\n| birth_place = [[Kuwait]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = Hameed Ali\n| nationality= Kuwaiti American\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = Author, spiritual teacher\n| influences = [[Ronald Fairbairn|Fairbairn]]{{\u00b7}} [[Sigmund Freud|Freud]]{{\u00b7}} \n}}\n'''A. H. Almaas''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|l|m|\u0259|s}} {{respell|AHL|m\u0259ss}}) is the pen name of '''A. Hameed Ali''' (born 1944), a [[Kuwaiti American]] author and spiritual teacher who writes about and teaches an approach to spiritual development informed by modern psychology and therapy which he calls the [[Diamond Approach]]. \"''Almaas''\" is the [[Arabic]] word for \"diamond\". \n\nAlmaas is originally from [[Kuwait]]. He is the spiritual head of the Ridhwan School. He may be described, among other things, as an [[Integral theory (philosophy)|Integral theorist]], [[mystic]], [[spiritual teacher]] and an exponent of the [[perennial philosophy]].\n\nAlmaas' books were originally published by the Ridhwan School, under the Diamond Books publishing title, but are now published by [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]].\n\nThe Diamond Approach is a contemporary spiritual path integrating the teachings and practices of the ancient wisdom traditions with modern [[depth psychology]] ([[object relations theory]] in particular). The Diamond Approach is derived from the experiences of Almaas, along with Karen Johnson and Faisal Muqaddam (who split off early on to develop his own approach). They were among the first students of [[Claudio Naranjo]], an early pioneer of the integration of spiritual and therapeutic work.\n\nThe curriculum of the work draws upon the founders' backgrounds in [[Sufism]], [[Buddhism]] and the [[Fourth Way]]. Teachers of the Diamond Approach focus on the students' specific perception of their own immediate work issues.<ref>https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/frequently-asked-questions-faqs#Who_can_teach \"Q: Who can teach the Diamond Approach?\"</ref> Presentation of a canonical body of knowledge and practice is introduced over time as required.\n\n== Life ==\nA. Hameed Ali was born in [[Kuwait]] in 1944. He was a victim of [[polio]] at 18 months old and now walks with a crutch as a result.<ref>{{cite news\n | author=[[Tony Schwartz (author)|Schwartz, Tony]]\n | title = Uncovering The Essential Self\n | work = New Age Journal\n | date = May 1995\n | url =https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/uncovering-essential-self\n | accessdate = 16 April 2020\n}}</ref> At the age of 18, he moved to the United States to study at the [[University of California]] in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]]. Ali was working on his PhD in physics when he reached a turning point in his life that led him more and more into inquiring into the psychological and spiritual aspects of human nature. His interest in the truth of human nature and the true nature of reality resulted in the creation and unfoldment of the Diamond Approach.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|last=Almaas|first=A.H.|title=A. Hameed Ali|url=https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/founders|website=diamondapproach.org}}</ref>\n\n== Diamond Approach ==\nThe Diamond Approach is a spiritual teaching that utilizes a distinctive form of inquiry into realization, where the practice is the expression of realization. Its aim is absolute freedom that can be described as living realization, a dynamic enlightenment where transcendent truth lives personally in the world. This inquiry opens up the infinite creativity of our being, transforming our lives into a runaway realization, moving from realization to further realization.<ref>{{cite web|last=Almaas|first=A.H.|title=The Diamond Approach \u2013 Hameed Ali (A. H. Almaas)|url=http://www.ahalmaas.com/|website=ahalmaas.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Ridhwan Foundation is the nonprofit spiritual organization established to support and preserve the integrity of the Diamond Approach teaching. The Ridhwan Foundation is legally recognized as a church and the role of a teacher is equivalent to that of a minister. People are ordained as spiritual teachers of the Ridhwan Foundation, which is the name given to its ministers.\n\n=== Spiritual practice as a phenomenology of being ===\nThe Diamond Approach is described as a \"response to an important need that is being felt in many quarters, a need for a spiritually informed psychology, or conversely, for a psychologically grounded spirituality. This perspective does not separate psychological and spiritual experience, and hence sees no dichotomy between depth psychology and spiritual work... This body of knowledge is not an integration or synthesis of modern depth psychology and traditional spiritual understanding. The inclination to think in terms of integration of the two is due to the prevailing belief in the dichotomy between the fields of psychology and spirituality, a dichotomy in which the Diamond Mind understanding does not participate.\" (Almaas)<ref>Almaas, A. H. ''The Void: Inner Spaciousness and Ego Structure'', Shambhala Publications, Boston MA, 1986.</ref>\n\nThe Diamond Approach, according to its followers, can be called a Phenomenology of Being that offers a precise description of the various aspects and dimensions of Spirit or Being and is also a form of [[Spirituality|spiritual]] psychotherapy which seeks to heal the wounds of the soul by reconnecting it to Spirit.\n\n=== Principal ideas ===\n\n==== Structure of reality ====\nIn the Diamond Approach, reality is seen as consisting of three elements: God/Being/Spirit, Soul/Self and World/Cosmos.\n\n''Being'' is understood as the inner source and true nature of reality, which is the focus of the great spiritual traditions of both East and West, and is known as ''[[Dharmakaya]]'', ''[[Shunyata]]'', ''[[Brahman]]'' or ''[[Tao]]''. Being is understood as consisting of five co-emergent \"boundless dimensions\": Divine Love, Pure Presence, Nonconceptual Awareness, The Logos, and The Absolute.\n\n''Soul'' is understood to be the individual consciousness that connects the world with Being, an idea found in ancient [[Chinese philosophy]]. It is believed in the Diamond Approach that the soul can be experienced as a living presence that contains the thoughts, feelings and sensations usually called our \"self\".\n\n''World'' is understood as the outer manifestation of reality, the multitude of physical forms that all people are familiar with.\n\n==== Essence and the essential aspects ====\nWhile most spiritual paths conceive of Being as universal, the Diamond Approach also pays a great deal of attention to a more individual way of experiencing Being, called Essence. The concept of Essence is similar to the Hindu idea of ''[[Atman (Hinduism)|Atman]]''. While Being is the true nature of all of reality, Essence is the portion of it that forms the true and personal nature of the soul. It is experienced as a substantial fluid Presence which can differentiate into various qualities or aspects, such as compassion, strength, will, joy, peace, love, value, humanness, personalness, identity, and space.<ref>Almaas, A. H. ''Essence'' Weiser Books, Boston MA, 1986.</ref><ref>[http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/e/essence.htm Essence & Spiritual Presence] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080707032123/http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/e/essence.htm |date=7 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==== Theory of holes ====\nAs our soul develops it is faced with a double challenge: it must learn to function in the World, while also remaining connected to Spirit. For various reasons, some innate and others environmental, we slowly become alienated from our Essence through the development of fixed patterns of perception and behaviour known as the personality or ego. Each of these patterns or ego structures disconnects us from a specific Essential Aspect. In other words, it is built around the \"Hole\" of this aspect. By exploring its structure, both cognitively and experientially, one eventually confronts the Hole and by going through it the lost aspect is retrieved.<ref>Ch. 2 \u2013 \"The Theory of Holes.\" Almaas, A. H. ''Diamond Heart Book 1'', Shambhala, 2000.</ref>\n\n=== Methodology ===\nThe Diamond Approach uses methods which its founders learned from Claudio Naranjo. Almaas' scientific background (he studied physics at Berkeley<ref name=bio />) helps explain the emphasis on rigorous (self) inquiry. Several contexts for participation are provided, including regular one-on-one sessions with a trained teacher, seminars and participation in various formats of organized ongoing groups.<ref>[https://www.diamondapproach.org/ways-to-engage Ways to Engage with The Diamond Approach]</ref>\n\n==== Presence ====\nThe practice referred to as \"presence\" is based on two methods, learning to sense one's body (especially one's arms and legs) in an ongoing manner and regularly focusing one's attention on a point in the belly called the \"kath center\" (known in Chinese philosophy as the ''[[dantian]]'' and in Japanese culture as the [[Hara_(tanden)|hara]]). These methods help a person to become more grounded in the body and in physical reality and also, in time, to develop the ability to experience oneself as the presence of Essence.\n\n==== Inquiry ====\nThe Diamond Approach centers on practice of investigation of the self, experience and perception.  \"Inquiry\" answers the question posed by [[Socrates]]: \"How does one set up as the object of one's investigation, that about which one knows nothing?\"{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}  One starts by wanting to find out, living a question, while recognizing preconceptions, preconditions and expectations as to the nature of what one may learn and instead attending to one's immediate or present experience. While not explicitly acknowledged as such, inquiry in effect combines (as a descriptive mechanism only, as the inquiry process is beyond mere language) the practice of [[Edmund Husserl]]'s \"transcendental phenomenological reduction, or epoch\u00e9\", with [[Sigmund Freud]]'s psychodynamic exploration. An important feature of inquiry is that a person learns to be aware of both the content of experience (emotions, thoughts, sensations) and the attitudes and reactions towards it. In this way the subject-object dichotomy is transcended and one learns to relate to oneself without having to create inner splits. Open-ended inquiry is both a path to, and the state of, a realized person and in time is understood to be a self-revelation of the mysteries of Being.\n\n=== Motivation ===\nThe main motivation for embarking on the spiritual journey in this approach is love for the Truth. \"Truth\" refers to seeing things as they really are, which ultimately comes down to recognizing Being as the true nature of everything. Love for the truth therefore combines the traditional [[bhakti]] and [[jnana]] perspectives on spirituality.<ref>https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/frequently-asked-questions-faqs#Goal_of_DA \u2013 \"Q: What is the goal of the Diamond Approach?\"</ref><ref>[http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/t/truth.htm Truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725054112/http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/t/truth.htm |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Critiques ==\nThe fees associated with the retreats and other methodologies that are part of the structure of the school have been criticized.<ref name=\"dailyCamera\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_12960184 |title=New path: Ridhwan teaches new way of looking at the world |date= 17 April 2009 | work=[[Daily Camera]]|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> However, the fees are relatively low compared to other spiritual schools and retreats.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}  Furthermore, the founder and lead teacher, Hameed Ali, regularly points out that the Diamond Approach is only one path to truth and cannot in itself be all-encompassing.  Students are permitted and even encouraged to question the practices of the school and to explore whether the school is a good fit for them personally.\n\nIn addition to the fees associated with the retreats, participants become provisional members of the Ridhwan Foundation (legally a church). After an unspecified designated period of time, they are asked to confirm membership by paying the appropriate membership fees to the foundation. These membership fees are $160/year for students involved in the group teachings and $60/year for provisional members.\n\nThe work of Almaas has received praise from spiritual teachers and explorers such as [[John Welwood]], [[Brant Cortright]], [[Gabor Mat\u00e9]], [[Jack Kornfield]] and [[Ken Wilber]].<ref>Wilber, K. ''Eye of the Spirit'' Shambhala: Boston, 1997 (372-373)</ref> Wilber, while tentatively supportive of the Diamond Approach, disputes some details. For example, he does not agree that infants have essential experiences, maintaining that the infant exists purely in the physical, material world \u2013 \"instinctual, vital, impulsive, narcissistic, egocentric; living for food, its God is all mouth.\"<ref>Wilber, K. ''Eye of the Spirit'' Shambhala: Boston, 1997 (362\u2013363)</ref> Almaas has responded that Wilber's critique demonstrates a misinterpretation based on Wilber's own linear, four-stage categorization of spiritual development. Almaas' perspective is that infants experience a type of true nature/Spirit, but one that is very distinct from, and less integrated than, the experiences of essentially realized adults.<ref>Appendix D in Almaas, A. H. ''The Inner Journey Home'', Shambhala: Boston, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Ridhwan School ==\nThe Ridhwan School is a loosely-knit affiliation of ongoing spiritual groups founded in 1976 by Almaas. The school is dedicated to the teaching of the Diamond Approach. It is principally based in [[Berkeley, California]] and [[Boulder, Colorado]] with other groups throughout North America and in parts of Europe and Australia.   Almaas is the spiritual head of the school and individual groups are taught by qualified Ridhwan teachers. The name of the school derives from the Arabic word for \"contentment\":\n\n<blockquote>\"Ridhwan is a kind of contentment which arises when you're liberated. Your personality becomes contented when you're free. Your personality itself is free from its suffering and conflict.\"<ref>''Diamond Heart, Book 2'', pg. 11 \u2013 [https://www.diamondapproach.org/glossary/refinery_phrases/ridhwan Book Excerpts about Ridhwan]</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe school rejects \"quick fixes\" and graduation, and the students are engaged in learning and therapy for an indefinite period.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=CSGB&d_place=CSGB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F34BBA41766BD2A&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Treating the Soul for Life: School rejects 'quick fixes' |date= 23 October 1992 | work=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)]]|accessdate=12 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''The Elixir of Enlightenment'', 1984, [[Weiser Books|Red Wheel Weiser]], {{ISBN|978-0-87728-613-4}}\n*''Essence: The Diamond Approach to Inner Realization'', 1986, [[Weiser Books|Red Wheel Weiser]], {{ISBN|0-87728-627-2}}\n*''Essence with The Elixir of Enlightenment: The Diamond Approach to Inner Realization'', 1998, [[Weiser Books]], {{ISBN|1-57863-044-4}}\n*''Facets of Unity: The Enneagram of Holy Ideas'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-14-4}}\n*''Luminous Night's Journey: An Autobiographical Fragment'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-08-3}}\n*''The Inner Journey Home: Soul's Realization of the Unity of Reality'', 2004, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-109-8}}\n*''The Power of Divine Eros''. Co-authored with Karen Johnson. [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], 2013 {{ISBN|978-1-61180-083-8}}\n*''Runaway Realization'', 2014, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|9781611802023}}\n*''The Alchemy of Freedom'', 2017 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|9781611804461}}\n* Journey of Spiritual Love Series\n**''Love Unveiled: Discovering the Essence of the Awakened Heart'', 2020 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1611808391}}\n* Diamond Mind Series\n**''The Void: Inner Spaciousness and Ego Structure (2nd Ed.)'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-06-9}}\n**''The Pearl Beyond Price'', 2000 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-02-1}}\n**''The Point of Existence'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-09-0}}\n* Diamond Heart Series\n**''Diamond Heart Book One: Elements of the Real in Man'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-01-4}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Two: The Freedom to Be'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-04-5}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Three: Being and the Meaning of Life'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-05-2}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Four: Indestructible Innocence'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-11-3}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Five: Inexhaustible Mystery'', 2011, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-906-3}}\n* Diamond Body Series\n**''Spacecruiser Inquiry: True Guidance for the Inner Journey'', 2002, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-57062-859-7}}\n**''Brilliancy: The Essence of Intelligence'', 2006, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-335-1}}\n**''The Unfolding Now: Realizing Your True Nature through the Practice of Presence'', 2008, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-559-1}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Enneagram of Personality]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://diamondapproach.org/ The Diamond Approach website]  \n* [https://www.shambhala.com/religion-philosophy/diamond-approach/ Shambhala Publications author page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080913110611/http://www.ahalmaas.com/PDF/Lighting_Up_the_Now.pdf Lighting Up the Now, a Free e-chapter from The Unfolding Now]\n\n{{New Age Movement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almaas, A. H.}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of religion]]\n[[Category:Mystics]]\n[[Category:Sufi psychology]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti writers]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti academics]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:Nondualism]]\n[[Category:Spiritual teachers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=March 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=March 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = A. H. Almaas\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1944\n| birth_place = [[Kuwait]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = Hameed Ali\n| nationality= Kuwaiti American\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = Author, spiritual teacher\n|influences = [[Ronald Fairbairn|Fairbairn]]{{\u00b7}} [[Sigmund Freud|Freud]]{{\u00b7}} \n}}\n'''A. H. Almaas''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|l|m|\u0259|s}} {{respell|AHL|m\u0259ss}}) is the pen name of '''A. Hameed Ali''' (born 1944), a [[Kuwaiti American]] author and spiritual teacher who writes about and teaches an approach to spiritual development informed by modern psychology and therapy which he calls the [[Diamond Approach]]. \"''Almaas''\" is the [[Arabic]] word for \"diamond\". \n\nAlmaas is originally from [[Kuwait]]. He is the spiritual head of the Ridhwan School. He may be described, among other things, as an [[Integral theory (philosophy)|Integral theorist]], [[mystic]], [[spiritual teacher]] and an exponent of the [[perennial philosophy]].\n\nAlmaas' books were originally published by the Ridhwan School, under the Diamond Books publishing title, but are now published by [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]].\n\nThe Diamond Approach is a contemporary spiritual path integrating the teachings and practices of the ancient wisdom traditions with modern [[depth psychology]] ([[object relations theory]] in particular). The Diamond Approach is derived from the experiences of Almaas, along with Karen Johnson and Faisal Muqaddam (who split off early on to develop his own approach). They were among the first students of [[Claudio Naranjo]], an early pioneer of the integration of spiritual and therapeutic work.\n\nThe curriculum of the work draws upon the founders' backgrounds in [[Sufism]], [[Buddhism]] and the [[Fourth Way]]. Teachers of the Diamond Approach focus on the students' specific perception of their own immediate work issues.<ref>https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/frequently-asked-questions-faqs#Who_can_teach \"Q: Who can teach the Diamond Approach?\"</ref> Presentation of a canonical body of knowledge and practice is introduced over time as required.\n\n== Life ==\nA. Hameed Ali was born in [[Kuwait]] in 1944. He was a victim of [[polio]] at 18 months old and now walks with a crutch as a result.<ref>{{cite news\n | author=[[Tony Schwartz (author)|Schwartz, Tony]]\n | title = Uncovering The Essential Self\n | work = New Age Journal\n | date = May 1995\n | url =https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/uncovering-essential-self\n | accessdate = 16 April 2020\n}}</ref> At the age of 18, he moved to the United States to study at the [[University of California]] in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]]. Ali was working on his PhD in physics when he reached a turning point in his life that led him more and more into inquiring into the psychological and spiritual aspects of human nature. His interest in the truth of human nature and the true nature of reality resulted in the creation and unfoldment of the Diamond Approach.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|last=Almaas|first=A.H.|title=A. Hameed Ali|url=https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/founders|website=diamondapproach.org}}</ref>\n\n== Diamond Approach ==\nThe Diamond Approach is a spiritual teaching that utilizes a distinctive form of inquiry into realization, where the practice is the expression of realization. Its aim is absolute freedom that can be described as living realization, a dynamic enlightenment where transcendent truth lives personally in the world. This inquiry opens up the infinite creativity of our being, transforming our lives into a runaway realization, moving from realization to further realization.<ref>{{cite web|last=Almaas|first=A.H.|title=The Diamond Approach \u2013 Hameed Ali (A. H. Almaas)|url=http://www.ahalmaas.com/|website=ahalmaas.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Ridhwan Foundation is the nonprofit spiritual organization established to support and preserve the integrity of the Diamond Approach teaching. The Ridhwan Foundation is legally recognized as a church and the role of a teacher is equivalent to that of a minister. People are ordained as spiritual teachers of the Ridhwan Foundation, which is the name given to its ministers.\n\n=== Spiritual practice as a phenomenology of being ===\nThe Diamond Approach is described as a \"response to an important need that is being felt in many quarters, a need for a spiritually informed psychology, or conversely, for a psychologically grounded spirituality. This perspective does not separate psychological and spiritual experience, and hence sees no dichotomy between depth psychology and spiritual work... This body of knowledge is not an integration or synthesis of modern depth psychology and traditional spiritual understanding. The inclination to think in terms of integration of the two is due to the prevailing belief in the dichotomy between the fields of psychology and spirituality, a dichotomy in which the Diamond Mind understanding does not participate.\" (Almaas)<ref>Almaas, A. H. ''The Void: Inner Spaciousness and Ego Structure'', Shambhala Publications, Boston MA, 1986.</ref>\n\nThe Diamond Approach, according to its followers, can be called a Phenomenology of Being that offers a precise description of the various aspects and dimensions of Spirit or Being and is also a form of [[Spirituality|spiritual]] psychotherapy which seeks to heal the wounds of the soul by reconnecting it to Spirit.\n\n=== Principal ideas ===\n\n==== Structure of reality ====\nIn the Diamond Approach, reality is seen as consisting of three elements: God/Being/Spirit, Soul/Self and World/Cosmos.\n\n''Being'' is understood as the inner source and true nature of reality, which is the focus of the great spiritual traditions of both East and West, and is known as ''[[Dharmakaya]]'', ''[[Shunyata]]'', ''[[Brahman]]'' or ''[[Tao]]''. Being is understood as consisting of five co-emergent \"boundless dimensions\": Divine Love, Pure Presence, Nonconceptual Awareness, The Logos, and The Absolute.\n\n''Soul'' is understood to be the individual consciousness that connects the world with Being, an idea found in ancient [[Chinese philosophy]]. It is believed in the Diamond Approach that the soul can be experienced as a living presence that contains the thoughts, feelings and sensations usually called our \"self\".\n\n''World'' is understood as the outer manifestation of reality, the multitude of physical forms that all people are familiar with.\n\n==== Essence and the essential aspects ====\nWhile most spiritual paths conceive of Being as universal, the Diamond Approach also pays a great deal of attention to a more individual way of experiencing Being, called Essence. The concept of Essence is similar to the Hindu idea of ''[[Atman (Hinduism)|Atman]]''. While Being is the true nature of all of reality, Essence is the portion of it that forms the true and personal nature of the soul. It is experienced as a substantial fluid Presence which can differentiate into various qualities or aspects, such as compassion, strength, will, joy, peace, love, value, humanness, personalness, identity, and space.<ref>Almaas, A. H. ''Essence'' Weiser Books, Boston MA, 1986.</ref><ref>[http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/e/essence.htm Essence & Spiritual Presence] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080707032123/http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/e/essence.htm |date=7 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==== Theory of holes ====\nAs our soul develops it is faced with a double challenge: it must learn to function in the World, while also remaining connected to Spirit. For various reasons, some innate and others environmental, we slowly become alienated from our Essence through the development of fixed patterns of perception and behaviour known as the personality or ego. Each of these patterns or ego structures disconnects us from a specific Essential Aspect. In other words, it is built around the \"Hole\" of this aspect. By exploring its structure, both cognitively and experientially, one eventually confronts the Hole and by going through it the lost aspect is retrieved.<ref>Ch. 2 \u2013 \"The Theory of Holes.\" Almaas, A. H. ''Diamond Heart Book 1'', Shambhala, 2000.</ref>\n\n=== Methodology ===\nThe Diamond Approach uses methods which its founders learned from Claudio Naranjo. Almaas' scientific background (he studied physics at Berkeley<ref name=bio />) helps explain the emphasis on rigorous (self) inquiry. Several contexts for participation are provided, including regular one-on-one sessions with a trained teacher, seminars and participation in various formats of organized ongoing groups.<ref>[https://www.diamondapproach.org/ways-to-engage Ways to Engage with The Diamond Approach]</ref>\n\n==== Presence ====\nThe practice referred to as \"presence\" is based on two methods, learning to sense one's body (especially one's arms and legs) in an ongoing manner and regularly focusing one's attention on a point in the belly called the \"kath center\" (known in Chinese philosophy as the ''[[dantian]]'' and in Japanese culture as the [[Hara_(tanden)|hara]]). These methods help a person to become more grounded in the body and in physical reality and also, in time, to develop the ability to experience oneself as the presence of Essence.\n\n==== Inquiry ====\nThe Diamond Approach centers on practice of investigation of the self, experience and perception.  \"Inquiry\" answers the question posed by [[Socrates]]: \"How does one set up as the object of one's investigation, that about which one knows nothing?\"{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}  One starts by wanting to find out, living a question, while recognizing preconceptions, preconditions and expectations as to the nature of what one may learn and instead attending to one's immediate or present experience. While not explicitly acknowledged as such, inquiry in effect combines (as a descriptive mechanism only, as the inquiry process is beyond mere language) the practice of [[Edmund Husserl]]'s \"transcendental phenomenological reduction, or epoch\u00e9\", with [[Sigmund Freud]]'s psychodynamic exploration. An important feature of inquiry is that a person learns to be aware of both the content of experience (emotions, thoughts, sensations) and the attitudes and reactions towards it. In this way the subject-object dichotomy is transcended and one learns to relate to oneself without having to create inner splits. Open-ended inquiry is both a path to, and the state of, a realized person and in time is understood to be a self-revelation of the mysteries of Being.\n\n=== Motivation ===\nThe main motivation for embarking on the spiritual journey in this approach is love for the Truth. \"Truth\" refers to seeing things as they really are, which ultimately comes down to recognizing Being as the true nature of everything. Love for the truth therefore combines the traditional [[bhakti]] and [[jnana]] perspectives on spirituality.<ref>https://www.diamondapproach.org/public-page/frequently-asked-questions-faqs#Goal_of_DA \u2013 \"Q: What is the goal of the Diamond Approach?\"</ref><ref>[http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/t/truth.htm Truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725054112/http://www.ahalmaas.com/glossary/t/truth.htm |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Critiques ==\nThe fees associated with the retreats and other methodologies that are part of the structure of the school have been criticized.<ref name=\"dailyCamera\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_12960184 |title=New path: Ridhwan teaches new way of looking at the world |date= 17 April 2009 | work=[[Daily Camera]]|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> However, the fees are relatively low compared to other spiritual schools and retreats.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}  Furthermore, the founder and lead teacher, Hameed Ali, regularly points out that the Diamond Approach is only one path to truth and cannot in itself be all-encompassing.  Students are permitted and even encouraged to question the practices of the school and to explore whether the school is a good fit for them personally.\n\nIn addition to the fees associated with the retreats, participants become provisional members of the Ridhwan Foundation (legally a church). After an unspecified designated period of time, they are asked to confirm membership by paying the appropriate membership fees to the foundation. These membership fees are $160/year for students involved in the group teachings and $60/year for provisional members.\n\nThe work of Almaas has received praise from spiritual teachers and explorers such as [[John Welwood]], [[Brant Cortright]], [[Gabor Mat\u00e9]], [[Jack Kornfield]] and [[Ken Wilber]].<ref>Wilber, K. ''Eye of the Spirit'' Shambhala: Boston, 1997 (372-373)</ref> Wilber, while tentatively supportive of the Diamond Approach, disputes some details. For example, he does not agree that infants have essential experiences, maintaining that the infant exists purely in the physical, material world \u2013 \"instinctual, vital, impulsive, narcissistic, egocentric; living for food, its God is all mouth.\"<ref>Wilber, K. ''Eye of the Spirit'' Shambhala: Boston, 1997 (362\u2013363)</ref> Almaas has responded that Wilber's critique demonstrates a misinterpretation based on Wilber's own linear, four-stage categorization of spiritual development. Almaas' perspective is that infants experience a type of true nature/Spirit, but one that is very distinct from, and less integrated than, the experiences of essentially realized adults.<ref>Appendix D in Almaas, A. H. ''The Inner Journey Home'', Shambhala: Boston, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Ridhwan School ==\nThe Ridhwan School is a loosely-knit affiliation of ongoing spiritual groups founded in 1976 by Almaas. The school is dedicated to the teaching of the Diamond Approach. It is principally based in [[Berkeley, California]] and [[Boulder, Colorado]] with other groups throughout North America and in parts of Europe and Australia.   Almaas is the spiritual head of the school and individual groups are taught by qualified Ridhwan teachers. The name of the school derives from the Arabic word for \"contentment\":\n\n<blockquote>\"Ridhwan is a kind of contentment which arises when you're liberated. Your personality becomes contented when you're free. Your personality itself is free from its suffering and conflict.\"<ref>''Diamond Heart, Book 2'', pg. 11 \u2013 [https://www.diamondapproach.org/glossary/refinery_phrases/ridhwan Book Excerpts about Ridhwan]</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe school rejects \"quick fixes\" and graduation, and the students are engaged in learning and therapy for an indefinite period.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=CSGB&d_place=CSGB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F34BBA41766BD2A&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Treating the Soul for Life: School rejects 'quick fixes' |date= 23 October 1992 | work=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)]]|accessdate=12 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''The Elixir of Enlightenment'', 1984, [[Weiser Books|Red Wheel Weiser]], {{ISBN|978-0-87728-613-4}}\n*''Essence: The Diamond Approach to Inner Realization'', 1986, [[Weiser Books|Red Wheel Weiser]], {{ISBN|0-87728-627-2}}\n*''Essence with The Elixir of Enlightenment: The Diamond Approach to Inner Realization'', 1998, [[Weiser Books]], {{ISBN|1-57863-044-4}}\n*''Facets of Unity: The Enneagram of Holy Ideas'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-14-4}}\n*''Luminous Night's Journey: An Autobiographical Fragment'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-08-3}}\n*''The Inner Journey Home: Soul's Realization of the Unity of Reality'', 2004, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-109-8}}\n*''The Power of Divine Eros''. Co-authored with Karen Johnson. [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], 2013 {{ISBN|978-1-61180-083-8}}\n*''Runaway Realization'', 2014, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|9781611802023}}\n*''The Alchemy of Freedom'', 2017 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|9781611804461}}\n* Journey of Spiritual Love Series\n**''Love Unveiled: Discovering the Essence of the Awakened Heart'', 2020 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1611808391}}\n* Diamond Mind Series\n**''The Void: Inner Spaciousness and Ego Structure (2nd Ed.)'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-06-9}}\n**''The Pearl Beyond Price'', 2000 [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-02-1}}\n**''The Point of Existence'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-09-0}}\n* Diamond Heart Series\n**''Diamond Heart Book One: Elements of the Real in Man'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-01-4}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Two: The Freedom to Be'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-04-5}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Three: Being and the Meaning of Life'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-05-2}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Four: Indestructible Innocence'', 2000, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-0-936713-11-3}}\n**''Diamond Heart Book Five: Inexhaustible Mystery'', 2011, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-906-3}}\n* Diamond Body Series\n**''Spacecruiser Inquiry: True Guidance for the Inner Journey'', 2002, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-57062-859-7}}\n**''Brilliancy: The Essence of Intelligence'', 2006, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-335-1}}\n**''The Unfolding Now: Realizing Your True Nature through the Practice of Presence'', 2008, [[Shambhala Publications|Shambhala]], {{ISBN|978-1-59030-559-1}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Enneagram of Personality]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://diamondapproach.org/ The Diamond Approach website]  \n* [https://www.shambhala.com/religion-philosophy/diamond-approach/ Shambhala Publications author page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080913110611/http://www.ahalmaas.com/PDF/Lighting_Up_the_Now.pdf Lighting Up the Now, a Free e-chapter from The Unfolding Now]\n\n{{New Age Movement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almaas, A. H.}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:American spiritual 