ion with [[PDP\u2013Laban]]\n\n==Notable Nacionalistas==\n===Past===\n{{Politics of the Philippines}}\nThroughout their careers, many of the country's politicians, statesmen and leaders were in whole or in part Nacionalistas. Notable names include the following:\n*[[President of the Philippines|Presidents]]:\n**[[Manuel L. Quezon]] (2nd President)\n**[[Jos\u00e9 P. Laurel]]<ref>Laurel was member of the NP before 1942 and from 1945\u20131959. During his tenure as President, he was affiliated with [[KALIBAPI]].</ref> (3rd President)\n**[[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]] (4th President)\n**[[Manuel Roxas]]<ref>During the 1946 presidential election, Roxas, who is a member of the liberal-wing of the NP, formed the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] and eventually moved there.</ref> (5th President)\n**[[Elpidio Quirino]]<ref>Moved to the Liberal Party during the 1946 presidential election.</ref> (6th President)\n**[[Ramon Magsaysay]] (7th President)\n**[[Carlos P. Garcia]] (8th President)\n**[[Ferdinand Marcos]]<ref>In 1978, Marcos left the NP and formed his own political party known as the [[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]] (KBL).</ref> (10th)\n**[[Joseph Estrada]]<ref>Estrada was a member of the NP during his term as Senator. In 1991, he formed his own party known as the [[Pwersa ng Masang Pilipino]] (PMP).</ref> (13th)\n*[[Vice President of the Philippines|Vice Presidents]]\n**[[Fernando Lopez]] (4th and 8th vice president under Elpidio Quirino and Ferdinand Marcos)\n**[[Emmanuel Pelaez]] (7th vice president under [[Diosdado Macapagal]])\n**[[Salvador Laurel]] (10th vice president and 5th and last prime minister under President [[Corazon Aquino]])\n'''[[Senate of the Philippines|Senators]]'''\n*[[Claro M. Recto]]\n*[[Jose Diokno]]\n*[[Blas Ople]]\n*[[Cipriano Primicias Sr.]]\n*[[Eulogio Rodriguez]]\n*[[Francisco Tongio Liongson]]\n*Manuel Briones\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Fuentebella]]\n*[[Miriam Defensor Santiago]]\n\nMost of these individuals embody solid political traditions of [[Economic nationalism|economic]] and [[Nationalism|political nationalism]] are pertinent today, even with the party's subsequent decline.\n\n===Current party officials===\nSome members of the House of Representatives and Senate include\u2014but are not limited to\u2014the following:\n*[[Manuel Villar]] (former Senate President), Party President\n*[[Cynthia Villar]] (current Senator), Party Chairman\n*[[Alan Peter Cayetano]] (current House Speaker), Secretary-General\n*[[Robert \"Ace\" Barbers]] (current Representative from Surigao del Norte), Spokesperson\n*[[Pia Cayetano]] (current Senator)\n*[[Imee Marcos]] (current Senator)\n*[[Lani Cayetano]] (current Representative from Taguig)\n*[[Lino Cayetano]] (current Mayor of Taguig)\n*[[Ralph Recto]] (current Senator e Senate President Pro Tempore)\n*[[Vilma Santos]] (current Representative from 6th district of Batangas)\n*[[Timmy Chipeco]] (Representative from Laguna)\n*[[Emmylou Tali\u00f1o-Mendoza]] (Vice Governor of North Cotabato)\n*[[Jose I. Tejada]] (Representative from North Cotabato)\n*Yevgyeny Vincente Emano (Representative from Misamis Oriental)\n*[[Antonio Trillanes]] (former Senator) (member of [[Samahang Magdalo]]/[[Magdalo Group]])\n*[[Bongbong Marcos]] (former Representative from Ilocos Norte and senator)\n*[[Imelda Marcos]] (former First Lady of the Philippines and Ilocos Norte Representative member of the [[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]] who caucuses with the NP)\n*[[Juanito Victor Remulla]] (former Governor of [[Cavite]], also a member of [[Lakas\u2013CMD]], [[Pwersa ng Masang Pilipino|PMP]] and [[United Nationalist Alliance|UNA]])\n*Elias Bulut Sr. (former Representative and governor from [[Apayao]] and Mayor of Calanasan, Apayao)\n*Rommel Jalosjos (former Governor of Zamboanga Sibugay)\n*Wenceslao Trinidad (former mayor of [[Pasay City]] Mayor)\n*[[Homer Saquilayan]] (former mayor of [[Imus, Cavite]])\n\n==Nacionalista-affiliated parties==\n* [[PDP\u2013Laban]]\n* [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino]]\n* [[Lakas\u2013CMD]]\n* [[National Unity Party (Philippines)|National Unity Party]]\n** [[United Bangsamoro Justice Party]]\n* [[People's Reform Party]]\n* [[United Nationalist Alliance]]\n* [[Team PNoy]]\n* [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]]\n* [[Marc Douglas Cagas IV|Alyansa]] \u2013 Davao del Sur and Davao Occidental\n* [[Alayon]] \u2013 Cebu\n* Kugi Uswag Sugbu \u2013 Cebu City\n* [[Partido Magdalo]] \u2013 Cavite\n* [[Vicente Emano|PaDayon Pilipino]] \u2013 [[Misamis Oriental]] and [[Cagayan de Oro]]\n* [[Fuerza Zamboanga]] \u2013 [[Zamboanga City]]\n* One Batangas \u2013 [[Batangas]]\n\n==Candidates for Philippine general election, 2010==\n{{main|2010 Philippine general election}}\n* [[Manuel Villar]] \u2013 presidential candidate (lost)\n* [[Loren Legarda]] \u2013 vice presidential candidate (lost)\n'''Senatorial Slate (11)'''\n* [[Pia Cayetano]] (won)\n* [[Bongbong Marcos]] (won)\n* [[Liza Maza]] (lost)\n* [[Ramon Mitra III]] (lost)\n* [[Satur Ocampo]] (lost)\n* [[Susan Ople]] (lost)\n* Gwen Pimentel (lost)\n* Ariel Querubin (lost)\n* [[Gilbert Remulla]] (lost)\n* [[Adel Tamano]] (lost)\n* [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]] (won)\n\n==Candidates for Philippine general election, 2013==\n{{main|2013 Philippine general election}}\n'''Senatorial Slate (3)''' ([[Team PNoy]])\n* [[Cynthia Villar]] (won)\n* [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] (won)\n* [[Antonio Trillanes]] (won)\n\n==Candidates for Philippine general election, 2016==\n{{main|2016 Philippine general election}}\n[[Candidates in the Philippine presidential election, 2016|Vice President]]: \n* [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] (lost)\n* [[Bongbong Marcos]] (lost)\n* [[Antonio Trillanes]] (lost)\n'''Senatorial Slate'''\n* [[Susan Ople]] (guest candidate of [[United Nationalist Alliance]] and Partido ng Galing at Puso) (lost)\n\n==Candidates for Philippine general election, 2019==\n{{main|2019 Philippine general election}}\n'''Senatorial Slate (3)''' ([[Hugpong ng Pagbabago]])\n*[[Pia Cayetano]] (won) \n*[[Imee Marcos]] (won) \n*[[Cynthia Villar]] (won)\n\n==Nacionalista Party presidents==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Term\n!Name\n|-\n|1907\u20131935||[[Speaker of the House of Representatives of the Philippines|House Speaker]] [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]\n|-\n|1935\u20131944||[[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Manuel L. Quezon]]\n|-\n|1944\u20131953||President [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]\n|-\n|1953\u20131964||[[Senate of the Philippines|Senator]] [[Eulogio Rodriguez]]\n|-\n|1964\u20131980||Senator [[Gil Puyat]]\n|-\n|1980\u20131989||Former House Speaker [[Jos\u00e9 Laurel Jr.|Jos\u00e9 Laurel, Jr.]]\n|-\n|1989\u20132003||[[Salvador Laurel|Vice President Salvador Laurel]]\n|-\n|2003\u2013present||Former [[President of the Senate of the Philippines|Senate President]] [[Manuel Villar]]\n|}\n\n==Controversy over dominant-minority status==\n\nIn the [[2010 Philippine general election|2010 general election]], the Nacionalista and the [[Nationalist People's Coalition]] (NPC) formed an alliance after it was approved by the [[Commission on Elections (Philippines)|Commission on Elections]] (COMELEC) on April 12, 2010.<ref name=\"SunStar\">{{cite web|title=NP-NPC coalition formally granted (5:15 p.m.)|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/network/np-npc-coalition-formally-granted-515-pm|work=[[Sun.Star Cebu]]|last=Alvarez|first=Kathrina|date=12 April 2010|accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> The Nacionalistas fielded Senator [[Manuel Villar]] and running with fellow Senator [[Loren Legarda]] who is a member of the NPC. It became the dominant minority party after a resolution passed by the COMELEC. On April 21, 2010, it was blocked by the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] after a suit filed by the rival [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]].<ref name=\"SunStar\"/> On May 6, 2010, the Supreme Court nullified the merger and therefore giving the Liberal Party to be the dominant minority party. It was based on a resolution by the COMELEC giving political parties to be accredited by August 17, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=SC nullifies NP-NPC coalition|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view/20100506-268401/SC-nullifies-NP-NPC-coalition|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|last=Torres|first=Tetch|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=9 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509162019/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view/20100506-268401/SC-nullifies-NP-NPC-coalition|archive-date=May 9, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe coalition was made to help the Nacionalista Party to help boost the presidential campaign of Senator Villar and have a chance to be the dominant minority party by the COMELEC which give the rights to poll watchers during the canvassing of votes.<ref name=\"Maragay\">{{cite web|title=NP-NPC coalition complicates fight in the local level|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/network/np-npc-coalition-formally-granted-515-pm|work=[[Manila Standard Today]]|last=Maragay|first=Fel V.|date=1 March 2010|accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> However, it is being challenged by the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] calls the said alliance a bogus alliance and they are seeking the same party status by the COMELEC.<ref name=\"SunStar\"/> Several local races are also being challenged from both parties, therefore causing confusion in those races.<ref name=\"Maragay\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Filipino nationalism]]\n* [[List of political parties in the Philippines]]\n* [[Liberal Party (Philippines)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|Nacionalista-Party-197002442379/}}\n* [http://countrystudies.us/philippines/18.htm The Jones Act]\n\n{{Philippine political parties}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n\n[[Category:Conservative parties in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Pro-independence parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1907]]\n[[Category:1907 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in Asia]]\n[[Category:Populist parties]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political party in the Philippines}}\n{{for|National and Nationalist  Parties in other countries|National Party (disambiguation){{!}}National Party|Nationalist Party (disambiguation){{!}}Nationalist Party}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Philippine political party\n| name = Nacionalista Party\n| native_name = Partido Nacionalista \n| logo = Nacionalista Party logo.svg\n| colorcode = {{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}\n| president = [[Manuel Villar]]\n| chairman = [[Cynthia Villar]]\n| secretary_general = [[Alan Peter Cayetano]]\n| founder = [[Manuel L. Quezon]]<br />[[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1907|4|25}}\n| headquarters = [[Starmalls|Starmall]] EDSA-Shaw 4F, [[EDSA (road)|EDSA]] corner [[Shaw Boulevard]], [[Mandaluyong]], [[Metro Manila]]\n| youth = Young Nacionalistas (YN)\n| ideology = {{nowrap|'''Modern:'''<br />[[Conservatism]]<ref name= \"Neoliberalism\"/><ref name=\"una\">Guillermo A. ''[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=wmgX9M_yETIC Historical Dictionary of the Philippines]''. Maryland, USA: Scarecrow Press. Retrieved 21 February 2019.</ref><br>[[National conservatism]]<ref>{{cite journal|year=2016|title=Weak State, Strong Presidents: Situating the Duterte Presidency in Philippine Political Time|volume=3|issue=3|first=Julio|last=Teehankee|journal=Journal of Developing Societies}}</ref><br />[[Populism]] (since 1946)<ref name=\"bertrand\">Bertrand, J. (2013). [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=AYMYAAAAQBAJ ''Political Change in Southeast Asia'']. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press.</ref><ref name=\"berneo\">Berneo, N.; Yashar, D. (2016). [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=Z9hsDQAAQBAJ ''Parties, Movements, and Democracy in the Developing World'']. New York: Cambridge University Press USA.</ref><br />'''Historical:'''<br />[[Filipino nationalism]] (1907\u20131978)<ref name=\"Liow\">Liow, J.; Leifer, M. (1995). [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=G5KLBQAAQBAJ ''Dictionary of the Modern Politics of Southeast Asia'']. New York: Routledge. Retrieved 16 October 2017.</ref>}}\n| position = {{nowrap|'''Claimed:'''<br />[[Big tent]]<ref name=\"berneo\"/><ref name=\"Neoliberalism\"/><ref name=\"cen\"/><br />'''Traditional spectrum:'''<br />[[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref name=\"upcpa\"/><ref name=\"una\" />}}\n| national = [[Coalition for Change (Philippines)|Coalition for Change]]\n| colors = '''National colors:'''<br />{{color box|#CE1126|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], {{color box|#0038A8|border=darkgray}} [[blue]], and {{color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[white]]<br />'''Customary:'''<br />{{color box|lightgreen|border=darkgray}} [[Shades of green|Light green]]\n| slogan = ''Ang Bayan Higit sa Lahat''<br />(The Nation Above All Else)\n| senate_seats = {{composition bar|4|24|hex={{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}}}\n| house_seats = {{composition bar|43|303|hex={{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}}}\n| governorships = {{composition bar|8|81|hex={{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}}}\n| vice_governorships = {{composition bar|11|81|hex={{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}}}\n| provincial_boards = {{composition bar|116|1023|hex={{Nacionalista Party/meta/color}}}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Nacionalista Party''' ({{lang-fil|Partido Nacionalista}}) is the oldest [[political party]] in the [[Philippines]] and in [[Southeast Asia]], responsible for leading the country throughout the majority of the 20th century since its founding in 1907, being the ruling party from 1935 to 1946 (under Presidents [[Manuel Quezon]] and [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]), 1953\u20131961 (under Presidents [[Ramon Magsaysay]] and [[Carlos P. Garcia]]) and 1965\u20131972 (under President [[Ferdinand Marcos]]).\n\n==Ideology==\nThe Nacionalista Party was initially created as a [[Filipino nationalist]] party that supported [[Philippine independence]] until 1946 when the [[United States]] [[Treaty of Manila (1946)|granted independence to the country]].<ref name= \"Neoliberalism\"/><ref name=\"Liow\"/><ref name=\"cen\"/> Since then, many scholarly articles that dealt with the history of political parties during the [[Third Republic of the Philippines|Third Republic]] agreed that the party has been increasingly [[populist]],<ref name=\"bertrand\"/><ref name=\"berneo\"/><ref name=\"cen\">Celoza, A. [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=Sp3U1oCNKlgC ''Ferdinand Marcos and the Philippines: The Political Economy of Authoritarianism'']. Connecticut, USA: Greenwood Publishing Group. Retrieved 19 September 2017.</ref><ref>Simbulan, D. (2005). [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=55ZQdJG1G6IC ''The Modern Principalia: The Historical Evolution of the Philippine Ruling Oligarchy'']. Quezon City: UP Press.</ref><ref>Del Rosario, Simon G. (1973). [https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=-Pw4AQAAIAAJ ''An Integrated Course on Communism and Democracy'']. SGR Research & Pub.</ref> although some argued they had [[conservative]]<ref name= \"Neoliberalism\"/><ref name=\"upcpa\">[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=nrAaAQAAMAAJ ''Philippine Journal of Public Administration, Volumes 34-35''] (1990). UP College of Public Administration. Retrieved 19 October 2017.</ref> tendencies because of their opposition to the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] and the [[Progressive Party (Philippines)|Progressive Party]]. The populist ideology of the party remained to present day as described on their website.\n\n==History==\nThe original Nacionalista Party that was founded on August 21, 1901 in Calle Gunao, Quiapo, Manila, was forgotten. In that Quiapo Assembly, the following officers of the true Nacionalista were elected, namely Santiago \u00c1lvarez and Pascual Poblete as presidents; Andres Villanueva, vice president; Macario Sakay, secretary general; Francisco Carre\u00f3n, Alejandro Santiago, Domingo Moriones, \u00c1guedo del Rosario, Cen\u00f3n Nicdao, Nicol\u00e1s Rivera, Salustiano Santiago, Aurelio Tolentino, Pantale\u00f3n Torres, Valent\u00edn Diza, Briccio Pantas, Lope K. Santos, P\u00edo H. Santos, Salustiano Cruz, Valent\u00edn Sol\u00eds and Jos\u00e9 Palma.\n\nThe party began as the country's vehicle for independence, through the building of a modern nation-state and the advocacy of efficient self-rule, dominating the [[Philippine Assembly]] (1907\u20131916), the [[Philippine Legislature]] (1916\u20131935) and the pre-war years of the [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]] (1935\u20131941). During the [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|Japanese occupation]], political parties were replaced by the [[KALIBAPI]].\n\nBy the second half of the century, the party was one of the main political contenders for leadership in the country in competition with the Liberals and the Progressives during the decades between the devastation of World War II and the violent suppression of partisan politics of the [[Ferdinand Marcos]] dictatorship.\n\nIn 1978, in a throwback to the Japanese occupation, political parties were asked to merge into the [[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]], although the Nacionalistas preferred to go into hibernation. Eventually, the party was revived during the late 1980s and early 1990s by the Laurel family, which has dominated the party since the 1950s. The Nacionalista Party is now being led by party president and former Seanator [[Manuel Villar]] and had three vice presidential candidates running independently or in tandem with other political parties ([[Alan Peter Cayetano]], [[Bongbong Marcos]] and [[Antonio Trillanes]]) in the [[2016 Philippine general election|2016 general elections]]. Two of the other present parties, the Liberal Party and the [[Nationalist People's Coalition]], are breakaways from the Nacionalista Party.<ref name=\"Neoliberalism\">Dayley, Robert (2016). [https://books.google.com/books?id=YCrTDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA195& ''Southeast Asia In The New International Era'']. Avalon Publishing. Retrieved 19 April 2017.</ref>\n\n==Electoral performance==\n===President===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Election\n!Candidate\n!Number of votes\n!Share of votes\n!Outcome of election\n|-\n|[[1935 Philippine presidential election|1935]]\n|[[Manuel L. Quezon]]\n|695,332\n|67.99%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1941 Philippine presidential election|1941]]\n|[[Manuel L. Quezon]]\n|1,340,320\n|81.78%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1946 Philippine presidential election|1946]]\n|[[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]\n|1,129,996\n|45.71%\n|Lost\n|-\n|[[1949 Philippine presidential election|1949]]\n|[[Jos\u00e9 P. Laurel]]\n|1,318,330\n|37.22%\n|Lost\n|-\n|[[1953 Philippine presidential election|1953]]\n|[[Ramon Magsaysay]]\n|2,912,992\n|68.90%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1957 Philippine presidential election|1957]]\n|[[Carlos P. Garcia]]\n|2,072,257\n|41.28%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1961 Philippine presidential election|1961]]\n|[[Carlos P. Garcia]]\n|2,902,996\n|44.95%\n|Lost\n|-\n|[[1965 Philippine presidential election|1965]]\n|[[Ferdinand Marcos]]\n|3,861,324\n|51.94%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1969 Philippine presidential election|1969]]\n|[[Ferdinand Marcos]]\n|5,017,343\n|61.47%\n|Won\n|-\n|[[1981 Philippine presidential election|1981]]\n|[[Alejo Santos]] (Roy wing)\n|1,716,449\n|8.25%\n|Lost as main wing boycotted\n|-\n|[[1986 Philippine presidential election|1986]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}} \n|{{N/A}}\n|Supported [[Corazon Aquino]] who won\n|-\n|[[1992 Philippine presidential election|1992]]\n|[[Salvador Laurel]]\n|770,046\n|3.40%\n|Lost\n|-\n|[[1998 Philippine presidential election|1998]]\n|{{N/A}} \n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|Did not take part\n|-\n|[[2004 Philippine presidential election|2004]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|Supported [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]] who won\n|-\n|[[2010 Philippine presidential election|2010]]\n|[[Manuel Villar]]\n|5,573,835\n|15.42%\n|Lost\n|-\n|[[2016 Philippine presidential election|2016]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|Supported  [[Rodrigo Duterte]] who won\n|}\n\n===Vice president===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Election\